We only have one function to fix: `parseOctal`. The fixed code should be exactly the same as the original but with the else-throw block replaced as above. Also, note that the while loop should be inside the if block. Also, we must keep the early return for buffer[offset]==0.

Let's write the fixed function:

```java
public static long parseOctal(final byte[] buffer, final int offset, final int length) {
    long    result = 0;
    int     end = offset + length;
    int     start = offset;

    if (length < 2){
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Length "+length+" must be at least 2");
    }

    if (buffer[start] == 0) {
        return 0L;
    }

    // Skip leading spaces
    while (start < end){
        if (buffer[start] == ' '){
            start++;
        } else {
            break;
        }
    }

    // Trim all trailing NULs and spaces.
    // The ustar and POSIX tar specs require a trailing NUL or
    // space but some implementations use the extra digit for big
    // sizes/uids/gids ...
    byte trailer = buffer[end - 1];
    if (trailer == 0 || trailer == ' '){
        end--;
        while (start < end - 1 && (buffer[end - 1] == 0 || buffer[end - 1] == ' ')) {
            end--;
        }
    }
    // If trailer was not NUL/space, we keep the full field.

    for ( ;start < end; start++) {
        final byte currentByte = buffer[start];
        // CheckStyle:MagicNumber OFF
        if (currentByte < '0' || currentByte > '7'){
            throw new IllegalArgumentException(
                    exceptionMessage(buffer, offset, length, start, currentByte));
        }
        result = (result << 3) + (currentByte - '0'); // convert from ASCII
        // CheckStyle:MagicNumber ON
    }

    return result;
}
```

Note: I removed the second `trailer = buffer[end - 1];` and the after-while loop because the while loop now uses the updated end.

